abstract: >-
  Multipath exploitation techniques have attracted considerable attention over the past decade, as they expand the detection coverage of conventional radar systems to Non-Line-of-Sight (NLOS) areas.  However, existing methods rely on fully or partially known reflector surface information to achieve detection and localization of NLOS targets, which poses challenges for practical applications since scene information is often not available  \textit{a priori}. To overcome this issue,  we present a multipath exploitation-based millimeter-wave (mmWave) multiple-input multiple-output (MIMO) imaging radar framework, which first performs  three-dimensional (3D) environmental perception and  then transfers the reflector surface parameters to assist  NLOS target reconstruction. To implement this process, we explore several key problems and propose corresponding solutions. First of all, we propose a joint multiple linear array beamforming (JMLA-BF)-based  imaging algorithm to achieve high-resolution sparse imaging as well as extract weak echoes of NLOS reflector surface. Then, an iteration algorithm is proposed for NLOS building layout recognition and relocation. Meanwhile, we propose an unambiguous  direction-of-departure (DoD) and  direction-of-arrival (DoA) estimation method for multipath signals from NLOS moving target using colocated MIMO radar. Finally, a path-oriented strategy is introduced to achieve NLOS target localization. Real experimental results demonstrate the effectiveness of the proposed framework and solutions in accurate 3D environmental perception and reliable NLOS target reconstruction.

